ABSTRACT
We present an open-access, open-source, interactive website for solving the Lippmann-Schwinger
(LS) integral equation for two-body (2B) bound states in two-dimensional (2D) momentum space, with
a primary focus on excitonic systems. The platform, available at
https://csu-physics.github.io/
2B_2D/
, combines concise theoretical primers with reproducible, browser-based Jupyter notebooks,
guiding users from problem setup through solution and visualization. Users can set physical and
numerical parameters, compute exciton binding energies and wave functions (e.g., with the Rytova-
Keldysh interaction), verify results via Hamiltonian expectation values, and assess convergence through
mesh-reﬁnement studies. To anchor accuracy, the website includes veriﬁcation case studies for the
2D hydrogenic atom (Coulomb) and the 2D deuteron (Malﬂiet-Tjon) before extending to excitons in
monolayer transition metal dichalcogenides (TMDs). The implementation emphasizes transparency
and extensibility, with modular solvers readily adaptable to any 2B quantum system in 2D. Designed for
advanced undergraduate and graduate instruction as well as research prototyping, the resource lowers
the barrier to LS-based calculations by unifying theory, computation, and interactive visualization in a
single, freely accessible environment.
1 Introduction
Excitons–Coulomb-bound electron-hole pairs in semiconductors and insulators–are canonical 2B quantum
systems. Their formation, binding energies, and radiative recombination govern key optical and electronic
responses and underpin technologies ranging from light-emitting diodes to photovoltaics
1–3
. In 2D
materials, reduced dielectric screening and quantum conﬁnement amplify excitonic effects, yielding large
binding energies and rich many-body phenomena conﬁrmed by precision spectroscopy in monolayer
TMDs
4–6
. Accurate modeling, therefore, requires methods that move beyond elementary approximations
and incorporate material-speciﬁc screening and band-structure inputs. The LS equation provides an
integral-equation formulation equivalent to the Schrödinger eigenproblem with appropriate boundary
conditions. For 2D excitons, both the bare Coulomb interaction and the Rytova-Keldysh (RK) potential are
widely used, the latter capturing nonlocal, environment-dependent screening characteristic of atomically
thin layers and their substrates
7–10
. Solving the LS integral equation in momentum space yields binding
energies and wave functions and enables controlled studies of dielectric constants, screening lengths,
and effective masses under experimentally relevant conditions. Momentum space LS techniques have
been successfully applied to diverse 2B bound states and provide a ﬂexible route for benchmarking and
extension
11–14
. To provide free, broad access, ensure reproducibility, and support teaching at scale, we
introduce a free, interactive online platform that uniﬁes theory, numerics, and visualization in a single
browser-based venue-no installation required and usable across devices-thereby removing platform barriers
and making LS workﬂows openly available to students and researchers alike. In this work, we introduce
an open-access, open-source website for solving the LS integral equation for excitonic systems in 2D
momentum space, available at
https://csu-physics.github.io/2B_2D/
. The platform couples
concise theoretical primers with browser-executable Jupyter notebooks (JupyterLite/Pyodide) to provide
end-to-end workﬂows-from parameter setup and quadrature discretization to solution, self-consistency
checks via Hamiltonian expectation values, convergence studies, and publication-ready visualization. Core
capabilities include (i) computing bound state spectra and wave functions for Coulomb and RK interactions;
(ii) interactive parameter scans with immediate feedback; and (iii) a modular, extensible design, so kernels
and models for 2D quantum systems can be adapted or extended with minimal effort. Designed for
advanced undergraduate and graduate instruction as well as research prototyping, the site lowers the barrier
to LS-based exciton calculations by unifying transparent methods, reusable components, and intuitive
interactivity in a single, freely accessible resource. To validate the formalism and support instruction,
the website also includes pedagogical testbeds that solve the LS equation for 2B problems: a hydrogenic
system (Coulomb interaction) and a schematic deuteron bound state (e.g., Yukawa-type/Malﬂiet-Tjon
(MT) interactions). These modules serve as clear numerical benchmarks and classroom assets before the
same toolkit is applied to excitons using the RK interaction.
The remainder of the paper is organized as follows. Section 2 presents the theoretical formulation;
Section 3 describes the numerical implementation; Section 4 reports applications to 2D hydrogenic,
deuteron, and exciton systems; Section 5 outlines the platform architecture and user interaction; and
Section 6 concludes. Appendix A summarizes the website development and technical details.

3 Numerical Implementation
To numerically solve the LS integral equation
(4)
for a 2B bound state in 2D, represented in the PW
framework, the integral equation should be transformed into a discretized form that can be solved
iteratively or through matrix diagonalization. To efﬁciently handle the integrals, variable transformations
are introduced to map the inﬁnite domains of momentum
p
, spatial coordinate
r
, and angle
φ
onto ﬁnite
intervals. The transformations are deﬁned as:
p, p
′
,r =
1+ x
1− x
, φ
′
= π(1+ x), x ∈ [−1,1], (10)
where
x
is a variable spanning the interval
[−1,1]
, suitable for integration using Gaussian-Legendre
quadrature. The discretized form of the integral equation for the wave function
ψ
m
becomes an eigenvalue
problem:
λ ψ
m
= K (E)ψ
m
, (11)
where
K (E)
represents the integral kernel operator dependent on the binding energy
E
. The eigenvalue
λ
is used as a criterion to verify the solution. The binding energy
E
is determined by solving for the
eigenvalue
λ = 1
. This involves iteratively searching over initial guesses for
E
until convergence is
achieved. A tolerance of
10
−6
is set for the eigenvalue condition, ensuring high accuracy in the computed
energy.
The iterative search procedure can be outlined as follows:
3/15
1. Select two initial guesses for the binding energy E.
2. Construct the kernel K (E) for each chosen energy.
3.
Solve the eigenvalue problem
λ ψ
m
= K (E)ψ
m
to obtain
λ
and the corresponding wave function
ψ
m
for both initial guesses.
4.
Using these two initial pairs
(E,λ)
, perform a linear ﬁt to predict the next energy value for which
λ = 1.
5.
Iterate the process with the updated energy values until
λ
converges to
1
within the speciﬁed
tolerance.
The kernel
K (E)
is diagonalized at each step, which allows for the extraction of both the eigenvalue
λ
and the wave function
ψ
m
. Efﬁcient numerical techniques such as matrix diagonalization, implemented
through libraries like LAPACK, or iterative solvers like the Lanczos algorithm
16
, can be employed for this
purpose.
4 Systems Studied
To ensure the robustness and accuracy of our computational framework, a critical ﬁrst step is validating
the numerical methods against established benchmarks. For this purpose, we compare our simulated
results for the 2D hydrogenic atom and the 2D deuteron system with well-known theoretical ﬁndings.
These systems serve as ideal case studies: the hydrogenic atom, with its fundamental Coulomb potential,
provides an exact analytical benchmark for bound states, while the deuteron, modeled with the more
intricate MT potential, demonstrates the framework’s ability to handle complex nuclear interactions. By
showing strong agreement between our computational outputs and trusted reference values, we establish
conﬁdence in the accuracy and reliability of our algorithms. This rigorous validation provides the essential
foundation for applying our methods to more complex systems, such as excitons in 2D materials, where
the RK potential is used to probe the inﬂuence of screening length and dielectric constants on binding
energies and wavefunctions.
4.1 Hydrogenic atom in 2D
We begin with the 2D hydrogenic system, a well-established case that provides an ideal benchmark for
testing the accuracy of our numerical method. In contrast to its three-dimensional analogue, the 2D system
exhibits distinctive features in its energy spectrum and wave function behavior arising from the reduced
dimensionality. In this section, we present both analytical and numerical treatments of the problem,
working in natural units where

4.3 Excitons in 2D Materials
Having validated the framework on 2D hydrogenic atoms and the deuteron, we now apply it to excitons-
bound electron-hole pairs formed by Coulomb attraction that play a central role in the optical response
of 2D materials. In this section we solve the LS integral equation for excitons using the RK potential.
This yields exciton binding energies and wave functions, providing insight needed to predict exciton
behavior in practical devices and to inform the design of materials with targeted optical properties. The
RK potential accounts for nonlocal, distance-dependent dielectric screening in 2D materials, and thus
models electron-hole interactions more accurately than a bare Coulomb potential. The explicit forms of

5 User Guide: Accessing, Editing, and Running the Interactive Code
The website hosts runnable Jupyter notebooks (via JupyterLite/Pyodide), so you can explore 2B quantum
bound state problems in 2D directly in your browser-no installation required.
5.1 Getting In
1. Navigate to https://csu-physics.github.io/2B_2D/.
2.
From the homepage, select a notebook from the top menu bar (e.g., Hydrogen in 2D, Deuteron in
2D, Exciton in 2D).
3. Allow a few seconds for the Python runtime to load.
4.
From the ﬁle browser in the left sidebar, open a Jupyter notebook (e.g., Hydrogen
−
2D.ipynb,
Deuteron
−
2D.ipynb, Exciton
−
2D.ipynb).
Visual cue: You will see the Jupyter toolbar (Run, Kernel, etc.) and executable code cells.

short search log. A typical printout for exciton:
" Sear ch 1 | BE2 = -0. 45 eV , Lamb da = (1 . 07 1 5 25 5 450 5 919 8 5 + 0j )"

5.5 Saving or Resetting Your Work
• Download your edits: Right-click a notebook (i.e. Exciton
−
2D.ipynb) and choose Download.
• Save ﬁgures: Select the plot, then drag and drop it onto your device.
• Reset to original: Refresh the page (sessions are ephemeral).
5.6 Troubleshooting
• Blank or unresponsive: Ensure JavaScript is enabled; refresh the page.
• Memory or speed issues: Reduce Np or Nphi; close heavy tabs.
• Stuck kernel: Kernel → Restart Kernel.
• No changes after edits: Run → Run All Cells.
5.7 Quick Checklist
1. Open a notebook and Run All once.
2. Edit Np, Nphi, m, and potential parameters.

6 Conclusion
We have released an open, browser-based platform for solving the Lippmann-Schwinger equation in two di-
mensions at https://csu-physics.github.io/2B
−
2D/. The website delivers executable Jupyter notebooks (via
JupyterLite/Pyodide) that implement the full workﬂow, from parameter setup and quadrature discretization
to numerical solution and binding energy calculations, validation via the Hamiltonian expectation value,
and visualization of wave functions. Case studies for the 2D hydrogenic atom (Coulomb), the deuteron
(Malﬂiet-Tjon), and excitons (Rytova-Keldysh) provide ready-to-run, momentum-space implementations
that connect theory with computation. Hosting on GitHub Pages ensures free, immediate access without
local installation, while the open repository invites community review and contributions (issues and pull
requests). This model promotes reproducibility, inclusivity, and rapid iteration on methods, examples,
and documentation. For education, the platform supports active learning with edit-and-run examples,
convergence studies, and interpretive plots that help students bridge abstract quantum concepts with
concrete numerical results. For research, it offers a transparent, reproducible environment for prototyping
kernels, testing discretizations, and benchmarking bound state solvers in 2D, lowering the barrier to entry
for new investigations of excitons and related 2B problems in atomically thin materials.
A Website Development and Technical Details
The interactive platform for solving the LS integral equation in 2D momentum space is hosted on
GitHub Pages at https://csu-physics.github.io/2B
−
2D/, providing free, browser-based access with no local
installation. Hosting on GitHub ensures version control, transparency, and community contributions
through issues and pull requests, enabling continuous improvement (e.g., new case studies or numerical
schemes) while keeping the resource openly accessible. The website is organized as executable Jupyter
notebooks (Python) that implement the full workﬂow: importing required libraries (e.g., NumPy/SciPy
for numerics and Matplotlib for plots), setting initial parameters (physical constants, material properties,
grid extents, and quadrature orders), applying Gauss-Legendre quadrature to discretize the continuous
variables (relative distance, relative momentum, and angular coordinates), assembling and solving the LS
integral equation, calculating binding energies, visualizing wave functions, and performing parameter
sweeps. The learning path includes a brief refresher on the Schródinger equation and the LS equation in
momentum space, with ready-to-run 2D implementations. Case studies demonstrate the framework for a
2D hydrogenic atom (Coulomb), a 2D deuteron (Malﬂiet-Tjon), and a 2D exciton (Rytova-Keldysh).
A.1 Front-End Implementation
A.1.1 Overview of Website Interface and User Interaction
The website was designed to be easy to use and focused on giving users an interactive experience. The
layout of the website is simple and intuitive, allowing users to easily navigate the different sections,
and interactive tools are built right into the pages, meaning users can run code, adjust parameters, and
immediately see results, all without needing to leave the website. This design philosophy aims to minimize
cognitive load and maximize engagement, allowing students to focus on the physics concepts rather than
the mechanics of the platform.
A.1.2 Description of Interactive Components, Visualization Tools, and User Controls
The website’s interactivity is delivered through embedded Jupyter notebooks that run entirely in the
browser via JupyterLite (Python kernel powered by Pyodide). Users can edit and execute code on the
page, adjust model inputs (e.g., potential parameters, and the number of mesh points for momentum/angle
discretization), and immediately recompute binding energies and wave-function plots. User controls and
12/15
visualization: Inputs are displayed as code cells in the Jupyter Notebook, and results update on run. Plots
rendered inline using Matplotlib, enabling quick comparisons and exploratory analysis. Environment
and workﬂow: No installation is required; notebooks load in seconds and run fully client-side. Users
can open hosted examples, modify them, and see results in real-time. The environment supports multiple
kernels and lightweight consoles for rapid experiments, providing a smooth, self-contained workﬂow for
learning and exploration.
A.1.3 Technologies Used
The website’s frontend is built with Next.js (React on Node.js), which provides routing, build tooling,
and both server-side rendering (SSR) and static-site generation (SSG) for fast, reliable delivery. After
implementing the core UI in Next.js, we integrated the interactive computation environment by embedding
hosted Jupyter notebooks in iframes. This approach cleanly separates the web application (navigation,
layout, performance) from the notebook runtime (code execution and visualization), while allowing the
interactive components to appear seamlessly within the website’s pages.
A.2 Back-End Implementation
A.2.1 Hosting and Deployment on GitHub Pages
We host the website on GitHub Pages for a simple, no-cost, and tightly integrated workﬂow. Changes
pushed to the repository trigger an automatic build and deploy (via GitHub Pages/GitHub Actions), so the
website stays current without manual steps or separate infrastructure. Because the website is served as
static HTTPS content with CDN caching, it loads quickly and reliably, and requires no application server
or container orchestration. This lightweight deployment model keeps maintenance minimal and aligns
with our goal of providing an easily accessible, always-available educational resource.
A.2.2 Technical Overview of Jupyter Notebook Usage
We build the interactive notebooks with JupyterLite and host them alongside the website, then embed
each notebook into the Next.js pages via
<iframe>
so students can open, edit, and run code directly
in the browser-no installs required. JupyterLite provides a full JupyterLab interface that runs entirely
client-side: a Python kernel powered by Pyodide (WebAssembly) executes in a Web Worker, enabling
numerical computing, plotting, and widget-based interactivity within the page. For this project we started
from an open-source JupyterLite template (GitHub) and tailored it to our content. To keep sessions clean
and secure, we disabled persistence, so any edits exist only for the current session and are not saved
to the server. Notes on capabilities and limits: Browser-based Python is ideal for teaching and demos
but has constraints: available memory is limited, package availability is narrower than a full desktop
Python, ﬁlesystem access is sandboxed, and heavy workloads may run more slowly than native execution.
Despite these trade-offs, JupyterLite delivers a fast, zero-setup environment thatâ

Zs well-suited to our
instructional goals.
